This is a general summary of the operation of the program:

    1. Task StartDefaultTask() calls upon a routine uart_puts() to send strings of text to the UART, one second apart.
     
    2. The function uart_puts() queues the characters in a message queue referenced by handle uart_txq. If the queue is full, control of StartDefaultTask() yields.
     
    3. Task uart_task() unqueues characters received from the queue referenced by handle uart_txq.
     
    4. Each character received is delivered to the UART to be sent, provided that it is ready. When the UART is busy, the control of the task yields.
    
I've also added the StartTask04 just to test out how the queue is working. Since the StartDefaultTask runs all at once it gets its entire message into the queue
without interruptions from StartTask04. Then StartTask04 puts its message into the queue twice since it only yields for 0.5s while StartDefaultTask yields for 1s.
The result is the following:

Task04
Task04
Now this is a message.. 
   send via FreeRTOS queues.

Task04
Task04
Now this is a message.. 
   send via FreeRTOS queues.
   
I am wondering if there is a way to preempt the default taks to get the Task04 message printed somewhere in the middle of the default task message?